        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We plan to observe in band 6 around a central frequency of 260 GHz, using two spectral windows with a bandwidth of 469~MHz, and one spectral window of 938~MHz, achieving in all windows a velocity resolution of about 0.6 km/s. The requested velocity resolution is adequate to resolve the typical linewidth, 2-3 km/s, of the target molecular lines and sufficient to properly sample the interval of LSR velocities, &gt;= 10 km/s, traced by the 6.7 GHz masers. We request the most extended (C34-7) configuration of the 12~m Array which achieves an angular resolution of 0.21", suitable to image both the rotating disk/envelope (with 0.3" &lt; size &lt; 3") and the jet (with full size &gt;= 3"). 
Our correlator setup will cover both typical "outflow" (SiO(6-5), H13CO+(3-2), SO2_5(2,4)-4(1,3)) and "disk" (CH3CN(14-13), CH313CN(14-13), C34S(5-4), CH3OH_5(0,5)-4(0,4)) tracers.
Interferometric observations with arcsecond angular resolution towards low- and high-mass molecular outflows derive brightness temperatures &gt;= a few K for different SiO lines ((2-1), see Cesaroni et al. 1999;  (5-4), see Gomez-Ruiz et al. 2013).
With a beam of about 3", the SMA 1.3~mm observations of the high-density molecular tracers in G16.59-0.051 achieved a main beam 
brightness temperature ranging from a few~K  up to 20~K  (see Fig.~3 from Beuther~et~al.~2006, where 1 Jy  is equivalent to a brightness temperature of 3 K). To ensure ALMA can detect transitions with intensity of (at least) a few K with  SNR &gt; 5, we need to reach a rms~noise of 0.5~K integrating over a typical linewidth (&gt; 1 kms)
of the target lines. According to the ALMA time estimator, the total 12~m Array time (including calibration and overheads) is 3.8~hours.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
